Grammarly is not a replacement for editing. I actually believe using it can cripple your writing skills. I had to correct so many mistakes it kept missing that I gave up on using it and told everyone I helped (I don't do that anymore) to stop relying on it as well.

I actually don't remember if I sent the advice or not, and I'm not going to check desu either, but my critique of the first chapter boils down to:
>not naming your main character in chapter 1
>starting with exposition that reads like a DM trying to explain his setting to the table before they roll characters, instead of a novel introduction
You should always introduce character(s), stakes, something important happening, or all three in your first chapter. You actually got me to dig up my copies of RA Salvatore to check how he did it in his first Drizzt novel. He did it several ways, not just one, at least in the copy I have

1
>demon irritated he doesn't have his mcguffin, and the statement that ends up in Faerun
2
>Drizzt's journal entry giving a glimpse into his mindset and trying to set the stage for what is about to happen
3
>description of a wizard caravan moving through the area, some info about the Dale, then it goes hard with the very next section beginning with a retarded (literally) wizard's apprentice stabbing his master

The amount conveyed in those first few pages is a lot, if you can handle the typical fantasy names thrown about. If you're inspired by these books then take inspiration from how they do story telling.
